  "response": "At the United Nations and other international conferences, several non-Arabic speaking countries use Arabic as an official or working language:\n\n1. Chad - Despite being a francophone country, Chad uses Arabic as one of its official languages and has significant Arabic-speaking populations.\n\n2. Eritrea - Although not primarily an Arabic-speaking country, Arabic is recognized as an official working language.\n\n3. Some African countries with significant Arabic-speaking populations or influences, such as:\n- Djibouti\n- Somalia\n- Sudan (which has a complex linguistic landscape)\n\n4. Some countries with significant Arabic-speaking minority populations might occasionally use Arabic in international settings, such as:\n- Iran (for Persian/Farsi speakers with Arabic connections)\n- Israel (for Arab-Israeli representatives)\n\nThese countries might use Arabic in diplomatic contexts, UN meetings, or international conferences based on their specific linguistic and cultural backgrounds.\n\nHowever, the primary users of Arabic in international forums remain the 22 Arab League member states, which are predominantly Arabic-speaking countries.\n\nThe actual usage depends on specific diplomatic contexts, delegation composition, and individual country practices.",
